ntsync 1010: NTSYNC_IOC_AGGREGATE_WAIT — heterogeneous PI-aware wait

Add a new ioctl on the ntsync device fd that atomically waits over
N ntsync objects + M file descriptors + optional absolute deadline,
returning the index of the first source that fired.  This is the
unified completion-handling primitive Wine has lacked.

Object sources reuse the existing obj->any_waiters list and the
existing PI-propagation paths (mutex pi_recalc, EVENT_SET_PI consume,
channel SEND_PI boost), so aggregate-waiters participate in priority
inheritance transparently.  Channel object sources are made notify-only
via four minimal hooks (is_signaled returns depth>0, try_wake_any_obj
dispatches to a new try_wake_any_channel_notify, send_pi calls it
inside the existing obj_lock window AND falls back to walking
any_waiters when recv_wq has no boost target) so the gamma-channel
dispatcher can wait on (channel, io_uring eventfd) atomically AND
correctly receive PI propagation from high-prio SEND_PI senders.
Userspace then issues NTSYNC_IOC_CHANNEL_RECV2 to actually consume
the entry.

Fd sources use the standard kernel poll machinery (one shared
poll_wqueues, vfs_poll(file, &pwq.pt) per source for registration,
vfs_poll(file, NULL) per source for level-triggered peek), mirroring
the WAIT_ANY uring_fd extension's pattern.

PREEMPT_RT discipline mirrors patches 1006-1009: all kmalloc/kfree
happen outside raw_spinlock_t; pi_work pool pre-allocated for any
mutex sources, drained on exit; empty pool falls back to silent
skip-boost (transient priority inversion, not deadlock).

Inherits wait_any's narrow signaled-vs-timeout race window between
schedule-return and the unqueue list_del — same trade-off, separate
fix if needed.

ABI: NTSYNC_IOC_AGGREGATE_WAIT _IOWR('N', 0x97, ...).  timeout/flags
follow NTSYNC_IOC_WAIT_ANY exactly (CLOCK_MONOTONIC ABSTIME ns,
U64_MAX = no deadline, NTSYNC_AGG_FLAG_REALTIME -> CLOCK_REALTIME).

NT semantics:
 - sem/mutex/event: unchanged from WaitForMultipleObjects (mutex
   acquired, auto-event reset, sem decremented on signal)
 - channel: notify-only (no NT equivalent; PeekMessage-style)
 - fd: pure Linux poll composition (no NT equivalent)

Channel SEND_PI any_waiters fallback rationale:

  Pre-patch SEND_PI walks recv_wq for the first blocked receiver.
  AGG_WAIT registers waiters on any_waiters (a different list).
  Without the fallback, an aggregate-waiting dispatcher would not
  be boosted by a high-prio audio thread's SEND_PI — kernel walks
  recv_wq, finds nothing, no boost.  Functionally fine (no lockup,
  dispatcher still wakes via try_wake_any_channel_notify) but a
  real PI regression for audio workloads.

  Fix: after recv_wq lookup yields nothing, walk any_waiters
  (priority-sorted; first entry is highest-prio waiter) under
  obj_lock briefly to find the boost target.  Symmetric with how
  EVENT_SET_PI works on event objects.

This patch is purely additive to existing Wine-using code paths:
 - is_signaled CHANNEL case: was always-false, now depth>0.  No
   existing caller passes a channel to WAIT_ANY/WAIT_ALL (channels
   use CHANNEL_RECV/SEND_PI/REPLY exclusively).  Zero impact.
 - try_wake_any_obj CHANNEL case: was no-op, now iterates an
   any_waiters list that is empty for channels in pre-1010 code.
   Zero behavior change for existing callers.
 - send_pi any_waiters fallback: only fires when recv_wq has no
   waiter AND any_waiters is non-empty (i.e., AGG_WAIT in use).
   Pre-AGG_WAIT code paths are unchanged.

